observations.recommendation:
We recommended that the Local Chief Executive:
Require the Municipal Accountant to coordinate with the Municipal Engineering Office to identify, determine, and reconcile those projects that were already completed and close the same to the appropriate PPE account;
Require the Engineering Office to provide the Accounting Office with copies of a comprehensive report of completed projects and other necessary documents;
Based on the adjusted data, require the Municipal Accountant to compute for the required depreciation on the completed projects, and accordingly adjust the balances of the affected accounts; and
Require the Municipal Accountant to restore the book value of the derecognized Construction in Progress (CIP) amounts and strictly comply with the COA's guidelines and procedures in the disposal of assets.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive:
Submit the authenticated APP and ensure attachment thereof to all contracts to be submitted, highlighting the projects therein;
Require the BAC to ensure that the contractor indicates the date of receipt in all the notices and documents received by them for proper computation of delays and/or slippage;
Require the timely issuance of Notice to Proceed seven (7) calendar days from the date of approval of the contract;
Ensure that all contractors including all its components are complete, particularly the exact date of contract date signing;
Submit proof of timely postings of the Notice of Awards and Notice to Proceeds in the PhilGeps for all the ensuing contracts; and
Require the BAC to attach in the submitted contracts the received copy of the invitations to all three (3) observers.

Require the Inventory Committee to conduct physical count of its road networks in order to ascertain the existence of the balance of the Road Networks account;

Direct the Municipal Engineer to provide the Municipal Accountant of the complete description and cost segregation of the road networks to facilitate the preparation of the subsidiary ledgers for roads and its components; and

Require the General Services Officer to prepare and maintain the Local Road Network Property Card for all roads and its components, including Road Map. A Report on Local Road Network is to be prepared by the General Services Officer at the end of accounting period.

Direct the GSO to strictly comply with the required physical count of all properties at least once a year, submit the CY 2021 Inventory Report to the Audit Team and submit a timetable for the conduct of physical inventory taking for CY 2022;

Direct the Inventory Committee to invite any representative from the Commission on Audit to witness the conduct of the actual physical inventory taking; and

Require the Municipal Accountant and GSO to maintain Property Ledger Cards and Property Cards, respectively and reconcile their records.

Require the Municipal Budget Officer to augment funds for the titling of the parcels of land enumerated in the inventory of lands;

Require the Municipal Assessor to coordinate with the General Services Officer in providing the lacking documents needed in the titling of the land; and

Direct the Municipal Assessor to prioritize the registration and the transfer of title of the land to the Municipality of Linamon.

Direct the Appraisal/ Inventory Committee to invite any representative from the Commission on Audit to witness the conduct of the actual physical inventory taking all properties, plant and equipment headed by the General Services Officer;

Require both the General Service Officer and the Municipal Accountant to maintain stock cards of each property, plant and equipment bearing property number and subsidiary ledger card on each equipment respectively;

The General Services Officer to identify unserviceable properties and prepare an Inspection and Inventory Report for disposal; and

The Municipal Accountant to prepare necessary adjustments on the deficiencies noted in the course of inventory taking and to make reconciliation with the inventory report, stock cards and subsidiary ledgers.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive:
Require the Municipal Accountant to determine the validity of the dormant payables and if found to have no legitimate claim against the Municipality, cause the reversion of the same to the unappropriated surplus; to use Accounts Payable instead of Other Payables when preparing an adjusting entry relative to stale/canceled checks; ensure that accounts payable are only recorded when the obligation is founded on a valid claim that is properly supported by sufficient evidence; and to adjust the balance of recorded obligations after full payment to unobligated allotment and the same shall be reconcile with the records of the Municipal Budget Officer;
Direct the Municipal Treasurer to exert more effort in coordinating with the employees and suppliers and send a written notice informing them of their unclaimed payables.

Direct the Municipal Accounting Office to:

Prepare and submit the JEV for depreciation expenses as well as the detailed lapsing schedule of all the PPE of the Municipality to validate the correctness of the presented balances in their Financial Statements;

Comply with COA Circular No. 2015-008 wherein all infrastructure assets are now being recognized in the books of the Municipality and correspondingly compute and record the correct accumulated depreciation;

Perform a thorough analysis of the PPE accounts and provide an explanation as to why certain types of PPE were not depreciated, otherwise make an adjusting entry to recognize all the accumulated depreciation from the date of acquisition of the affected assets and record it in the books accordingly; and

Include in the Notes to Financial Statements the full disclosure of the estimated useful life for all PPE accounts and provide an explanation on the non-provision of any residual value for all PPE of the Municipality.

Direct the Municipal Accountant to closely monitor cash advances and compel all accountable officers to produce without delay their liquidation reports together with supporting documents, and to further require the immediate refund of all unused cash advances;

Require officials & employees who are retiring from the government service to settle their cash advances prior to the issuance of clearance from money and property accountabilities;

Conduct thorough review and evaluation of the affected dormant accounts, if any, and comply with all the documentary requirements and procedures under COA Circular No. 2016-005 for the request of write-off of dormant accounts and the disclosure thereof;

Direct the Accountant to prepare the quarterly aging of dormant unliquidated cash advances to support the request for write-off, if any; and

Ensure that all applicable laws, rules and regulations affecting cash advances are strictly adhered to.

We recommended the Local Chief Executive to:
Require the MPDC to provide specific target dates of implementation of the PPAs and the related target schedule for each procurement activities in order to ensure timely implementation of projects;
Require the MPDC and Municipal Budget Office to review and assess the unimplemented projects /unobligated fund from prior years and the LCE to consider the possibility of proposing and re-appropriation to other priority development projects;
Instruct the Municipal Engineer and Municipal Planning and Development Coordinator to conduct regular monitoring and evaluation of the projects and at the same time respond to the causes of delays based on the actual implementation; and
Revisit guidelines in the preparation of budget for 20% Local Government Development Fund to ensure responsive estimate of project cost.

We have recommended to the Municipal Treasurer to:

Restrict access to cash accountable forms & their records to authorized personnel only to reduce the risk unauthorized use and/ or loss to the government;

Strictly implement the procedures on the requisitions of accountable form and daily turnover of collections to strengthen the Municipality’s control over collections;

See to it that all collectors are properly supervised and their accountabilities are regularly monitored; and

Require the erring accountable officer to remit the collections, and record, update and submit the cashbooks, RCD/RCR to COA, if issued; to present the missing accountable forms to COA, if unissued; or to give notice of loss in accordance of COA Circular no. 84-233 dated August 12, 1984.

We recommend to the Municipal Treasurer to:

Strengthen its internal control over cash and accountable forms, identify its weakness, and monitor the implementation of stricter internal control on cash transactions;

Monitor the Accountable Forms issued to the AOs by only releasing stubs one at a time, to issue the same in strict numerical sequence and to see to it that remittances was made to avoid loss or misappropriation; and prohibit the erring accountable officer from handling cash and collections of the Municipality.

We have recommended to the Local Chief Executive the following:

Instruct the Municipal Treasurer to require the Collecting Officers especially the revenue collectors to maintain cashbook for easy monitoring of all collections;

If possible, the Municipal Treasurer should reorient the Collecting Officers of their duties and responsibilities and teach them how to handle properly their cashbooks or recommend them to attend virtual seminars;

 Require the Municipal Treasurer to update her cashbooks quarterly with the Municipal Accountant for reconciliation; and

If the budget warrants, hire additional personnel to assist the Municipal Treasurer in maintaining and monitoring properly her cashbooks.

